[1]
Date: 17 Sep 2004
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: WNNE 31 [edited]
<http://www.thechamplainchannel.com/wnne/3738861/detail.html>

Horse death prompts mosquito warning in Kingston
-------------------------------------
State health officials are urging residents around Kingston to
protect themselves against mosquitoes, after a horse died of Eastern
equine encephalitis. The virus is transmitted through the bite of an
infected mosquito.
The horse died last month [August 2004]. It's the 1st known casualty
of the disease in New Hampshire in 22 years. The disease rarely
affects people, but, can cause mild flu-like problems, coma and even
death.
Mosquitoes carrying Eastern equine encephalitis have been discovered
in several communities in southeastern Massachusetts. A 64-year-old
Brockton man, and a 13-year-old boy from Holbrook, died from the
disease last month [August 2004]. They were the 1st human cases in
Massachusetts since 1995.
--
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>
[Although neighboring states have had EEE in previous years, the NH
state veterinarian's office confirmed that this is the 1st time in
several decades that it has been in NH. - Mod.TG]
